content:
Queuing options in Chat let you control how incoming chat requests are handled when no agents are available.

Available in: Salesforce Classic and Lightning Experience, Performance Editions, Developer Edition orgs created after June 14, 2012, Essentials, Unlimited, and Enterprise Editions with Service Cloud or Sales Cloud.

The legacy chat product is scheduled for retirement on February 14, 2026. To avoid service interruptions, migrate to Messaging for In-App and Web before that date.

For each chat button or invitation, you can enable queuing, which puts incoming requests on hold if no qualified agents are available. You can specify the maximum number of requests in a queue.

Queuing helps agents work effectively and limits customer wait time. Chat routing options determine how queuing works.

Here's how queuing and routing options work together:

* Queuing is not enabled: Choice - Customers see the chat button, incoming requests are added to the Chat Requests list.
* Queuing is not enabled: Least Active or Most Available - Customers see the chat button, requests are routed to agents when capacity is available.
* Queuing is enabled without a limit: Choice - Customers see the chat button, incoming requests are added to the queue until capacity is available.
* Queuing is enabled without a limit: Least Active or Most Available - Customers see the chat button, requests are routed to agents when capacity is available.
* Queuing is enabled with a limit: Choice - Customers see the chat button until the queue limit is reached, then an offline version of the button appears until older sessions have ended and an agent is available.
* Queuing is enabled with a limit: Least Active or Most Available - Customers see the chat button until the queue limit is reached, then users see the offline version until older sessions have ended and an agent is available.
title: Understanding Chat Queuing in Service Cloud
